<figureCitation box="[408,485,1336,1358]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="10.[196,235,1370,1389]" captionTargetBox="[178,1001,194,1347]" captionTargetId="figure-1@10.[178,1001,194,1347]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs. 25–32. Geraeus and Linogeraeus species, dorsal and lateral aspects; scale bar 1 mm. 25, 26) G. minor, male; 27, 28) G. petilior, male; 29, 30) G. picumnus, male; 31, 32) L. crucifer, male." pageId="20" pageNumber="143">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
); integument black, distal portion of appendages often brown or reddish; scales white, elongate on dorsal side of body, wider and denser on ventral side and on pleurites (particularly in Mexican specimens); rostrum stout, evenly curved, gradually tapered, dorsal profile continuous with head, male 1.06–1.23X length of pronotum, female 1.08–1.23X length of pronotum (
<collectingCountry box="[296,330,1469,1491]" name="United States of America" pageId="20" pageNumber="143">US</collectingCountry>
specimens in lower range), anteantennal portion of male 0.37– 0.41X length of rostrum, of female 0.35–0.45X length of rostrum (
<collectingCountry box="[861,895,1495,1517]" name="United States of America" pageId="20" pageNumber="143">US</collectingCountry>
specimens in upper range), male without tubercle on submentum, funicle stout, club rather large; pronotum with greatest width at base, sides roundly narrowed to front, apical constriction subtle, dorsal punctation shallow and separate; prosternum unmodified, spines and folds absent, posterior line of tubulate constriction with moderately deep punctures, scales not radiating from central pore; elytral interstriae mostly with 2 more or less regular rows of appressed, elongate, white scales; male with ventrites 1 and 2 slightly depressed, both genders with ventrite 5 with apical depression; all legs with ventrodistal tibial spine; body of aedeagus dorsoventrally compressed, dorsal aspect as in 
<figureCitation box="[623,697,356,378]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="14.[196,235,1336,1355]" captionTargetBox="[191,987,194,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-64@14.[191,988,194,1314]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs. 57–60. Geraeus and Linogeraeus species, aedeagus, dorsal aspect; scale bars" pageId="21" pageNumber="144">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
, internal sac slightly longer than apodemes, surface with non-sclerotized asperities, gonopore without sclerite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="144" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[146,976,194,597]" pageId="21" pageNumber="144">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[170,296,411,433]" pageId="21" pageNumber="144">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is known from central 
<collectingCountry box="[705,781,411,433]" name="Mexico" pageId="21" pageNumber="144">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and extends into southern Arizona (
<figureCitation box="[342,419,438,460]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="19.[167,206,1405,1424]" captionTargetBox="[147,973,194,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-0@19.[147,973,194,1382]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs. 73–75. Maps of southern United States and Mexico (top) and United States (without northwestern part) and Central America (bottom) showing distributions of G. euryonyx, G. minor, G. nimbatus, G. pannuceus, G. patagoniensis, G. petilior, and Linogeraeus neglectus." pageId="21" pageNumber="144">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[146,976,194,597]" box="[170,658,466,488]" pageId="21" pageNumber="144">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[170,387,466,488]" pageId="21" pageNumber="144">Temporal occurrence.</emphasis>
July to October [7 dates].
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[146,976,194,597]" pageId="21" pageNumber="144">
